The paper deals with optimization of trajectories for parameter estimation in a dynamic system, which falls under the category of control systems (cs.SY). The optimization algorithm is formulated to maximize the Fisher information matrix (FIM), which is a statistical measure of the amount of information that an observable random variable X carries about an unknown parameter θ of a distribution that models X. This involves optimization techniques such as gradient descent and Hessian matrix calculations, which are commonly used in optimization (cs.Optimization). The paper also involves experiments with a double-pendulum cart apparatus, which is a robotic system, falling under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The paper also involves numerical simulations, which can be considered as a machine learning approach (cs.LG). Finally, the paper involves the use of optimization techniques to improve parameter estimation, which is a common problem in neural networks (cs.NEURAL).
